Having the transfer case in &quot;N&quot; effectively immobilizes the vehicle since it
disengages the drivetrain (engine, trans.) from the front/rear axle. This is
normal. The t-case should have a &quot;2-H&quot; gear, which is what you should use
for street applications. Running the truck in &quot;4L / 4H&quot; puts unecessary
wear on your drivetrain and reduces mileage substantially. You may have to
install a part time kit in your truck if its one of the ones that came
factory with full-time four wheel drive. This involves changing the hubs to
manual units and in some cases (depending on your transfer case) requires a
slight modification of the transfer case. This is a definate worthwhile
upgrade to do! Some of the grinding noises you are experiencing are normal
if you can belive that. Hope this helps. -Dave

